While it is widely known that insulin resistance is a central feature of type
2 diabetes and pre-diabetes, it is less well known that it can also affect
The term ‘double diabetes’ was coined in 2001, and describes people with type
1 diabetes autoantibodies who also develop insulin resistance.
The normal action of the hormone insulin helps manage blood glucose levels by
moving glucose from the blood into muscles, fat cells, and the liver to be
When you are insulin resistant, the body has built up a tolerance to the
actions of insulin, and insulin is less effective in doing its job. As a
result, more insulin may be required to coax the cells and liver to take up
Insulin resistance is what contributes to the increased insulin requirements
usually seen in people with type 1 diabetes during puberty, pregnancy and
* Carrying extra weight (especially around the waist)
* Certain ethnic groups (eg South East Asian, Indian, North African, Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islanders, Maori, and Polynesian)
Intensive insulin therapy, increasing insulin dose requirements, recurrent
hypoglycaemia and excessive snacking may contribute to weight gain and insulin
Now for the good news! Being more active can make the body more sensitive to
insulin in the short and long term. Regular exercise and resistance training
helps build muscle and can open up an alternative pathway for glucose to enter
muscle cells without insulin as a mediator. This reduces the cells’ dependence
on insulin for energy, and can improve blood glucose levels.
If you are overweight, losing weight can improve insulin resistance. Weight
loss can be achieved by maintaining a healthy diet and regular exercise.
Eating five serves of veggies and two pieces of fruit per day and limiting
your intake of processed foods, cakes, biscuits, and fried takeaway foods can
If your insulin requirements are increasing despite maintaining a fairly
consistent diet you should speak to your doctor or diabetes educator. Insulin
resistance may be playing a role. Insulin resistance makes managing your
diabetes more difficult and increases your risk of developing cardiovascular
If you need support to get more active or with healthy eating, an exercise
